[[File:Khanyi Dhlomo.jpg|thumb|right|160px|Khanyi Dhlomo (2014)]]
'''Khanyi Dhlomo''' (born 17 December 1974 in Umlazi, [[KwaZulu-Natal]]) is a South African TV Host and the founder and CEO of [[Ndalo Media]] and Ndalo Luxury Ventures.

==Early life==
Dhlomo is the daughter of [[Oscar Dhlomo]]{{efn|Oscar Dhlomo was member of the KwaZulu Legislative Assembly for Umbumbulu, Minister of Education and Culture, KwaZulu, Secretary General, Inkatha yeNkululeko yeSizwe, Executive Chairman, Institute for Multi-Party Democracy<ref name="SAHO">{{Cite web | title = Oscar Dumisani Dhlomo | author =  | work = South African History Online | date =  | accessdate = 2016-07-25 | url = http://www.sahistory.org.za/people/oscar-dumisani-dhlomo | language =   | quote =  }}</ref>
 }} She went to school at [[ Durban Girls' College]], in [[Durban]], while there she won the Thandi Face Cover Girl competition at the age of 16,<ref>{{cite web|title = Who is Khanyi Dhlomo?|url = http://mg.co.za/article/2013-07-31-who-is-khanyi-dlhomo|work = Mail & Guardian|accessdate = 29 April 2014}}</ref> which sparked her interest in media.

==Career==
At the age of 22 Dhlomo was appointed as editor of the magazine, ''True Love''. Within a year of her appointment, the magazine's circulation doubled<ref>{{cite web|title=Winning Women – Khanyi Dhlomo: The glimmer of success |url=http://www.citypress.co.za/business/winning-women-khanyi-dhlomo-the-glimmer-of-success/ |work=City Press |accessdate=29 April 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421223119/http://www.citypress.co.za/business/winning-women-khanyi-dhlomo-the-glimmer-of-success/ |archivedate=21 April 2014 |df= }}</ref> from 70,000 to 140,000 and the magazine became the most widely read women's magazine in the country.

After eight years at ''True Love'' with a circulation of 1.9 million, Dhlomo stepped down as editor. Following the end of her first marriage she relocated to France where she worked as manager of South Africa's Tourism Board in Paris. In 2007 she graduated from [[Harvard Business School]] with an MBA which is where she met her second husband Chinezi Chijioke.

In 2007 she returned home to South Africa at which time she founded Ndalo Media in partnership with [[Naspers]] and successfully published the magazine, [[Destiny (magazine)|Destiny]]. In 2008 Dhlomo launched DestinyConnect.com which serves as the online extension of Destiny magazine and in July 2009 Destiny Man, edited by [[Kojo Baffoe]] was launched together with its online extension DestinyMan.com.<ref>{{cite web|title=Africas Most Successful Women – Khanyi Dhlomo|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/mfonobongnsehe/2011/06/06/africas-most-successful-women-khanyi-dhlomo/|work=Forbes|accessdate=30 April 2014|author=Mfonobong Nsehe|date=6 June 2011}}</ref>

In 2013, Dhlomo launched the boutique department store, Luminance.<ref>{{cite web|title=Luminance boutique department store launches in Hyde Park|url=http://www.destinyconnect.com/2013/07/26/luminance-boutique-department-store-launches-in-hyde-park/|work=Destiny Connect|accessdate=2 May 2014}}</ref>

==Awards==
*2001 AdVantage Magazine Editor of the Year{{cn|date=July 2016}}
*Most Influential Woman in South African Media 2003{{cn|date=July 2016}}

